{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513539","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513539"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:10:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:10:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12153"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12153","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12153"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.81,0.13,0.02,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4683"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100027"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4683","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4683"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12153"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82419"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1730"},{"type":"tags","id":"2040"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7214"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8024"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100027","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/100027"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 43-year-old woman undergoes a total thyroidectomy for follicular carcinoma. The procedure is uneventful and she is recovering well. However, two days after the procedure she notices tingling and numbness in her hands and around her mouth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her blood pressure is 110/80 mmHg, pulse 80/min, temperature 37.8 \u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC, and respiratory rate is 17/min. She has positive Chovstek and Trousseau signs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"A deficiency in which one of the following hormones is most likely responsible for her current clinical picture?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["1,25 Vitamin D","Parathyroid hormone","Calcitonin","T4","25 Vitamin D"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely explanation for this patient\u0027s current symptoms is hypocalcaemia, which might be the result of inadvertent damage to the parathyroid glands during her recent thyroid surgery. Total thyroidectomy does not cause hypocalcaemia unless parathyroid gland function is unintentionally impacted. A positive Chovstek sign is seen when tapping over the facial nerve immediately in front of the ear produces abnormal twitching of the facial muscles. A Trousseau\u0027s sign can be elicited when inflation of a blood pressure cuff on the upper arms causes carpopedal spasm. Both these signs are associated with hypocalcaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo assess the aetiology of her hypocalcaemia, the measurement of serum intact \u003Cstrong\u003Eparathyroid hormone (PTH) \u003C/strong\u003Eis the most valuable test and should be performed in all patients with hypocalcaemia. A suppressed or \u201cinappropriately low\u201d PTH level in the setting of hypocalcemia establishes absent or reduced PTH secretion as the cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnce the PTH has been tested, proceeding to testing vitamin D can be helpful (but not before). \u003Cstrong\u003E25-vitamin D \u003C/strong\u003Edeficiency is contributory in many cases of hypocalcemia post-thyroidectomy. There is evolving evidence which suggests replenishing \u003Cstrong\u003E25-vitamin D \u003C/strong\u003Epre-operatively prevents hypocalcemia. \u003Cstrong\u003E1,25-vitamin D\u003C/strong\u003E (i.e. calcitriol) is used to treat severe hypocalcemia that fails to respond to supplemental calcium and 25-vitamin D.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMeasuring \u003Cstrong\u003ET4\u003C/strong\u003E will not be helpful to determine the cause of the hypocalcaemia. The endogenous T4 will be low as the thyroid gland has been removed (and this will be replaced with exogenous thyroxine replacement). It is important to note that hyperthyroidism pre-operatively predisposes to hungry bone syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMeasuring \u003Cstrong\u003Ecalcitonin\u003C/strong\u003E will not be helpful to determine the cause of the hypocalcaemia. This hormone\u0027s effect on calcium homeostasis is weak. Furthermore, total thyroidectomy removes the C cells.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Determining the PTH level is central to the evaluation of hypocalcaemia.","A suppressed or \u201cinappropriately low\u201d PTH level in the setting of hypocalcaemia establishes absent or reduced PTH secretion as the cause."],"references":["Cooper MS, Gittoes NJ. Diagnosis and management of hypocalcaemia. BMJ. 2008 Jun 7;336(7656):1298-302.","Hannan FM, Thakker RV. Investigating hypocalcaemia. BMJ. 2013 May 9;346:f2213."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82419"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12153"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82419","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/82419"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-23T20:58:16+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-23T20:58:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4683"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100027"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedi